The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, February 06, 2004 				 Xansa to raise India headcount
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Mumbai, Feb. 5: UK-based Xansa will invest 24 million in India to raise the capacity of its development centres to 10,000 seats on a single-shift basis.																								Xansa chief executive officer Alistair Cox said the company has been growing rapidly in India and it has increased its headcount by over 50 per cent since May. He was speaking on the sidelines of Nasscom 2004 India Leadership Forum here today.																								Xansa has been operating in India since 1989. It has recently opened two centres at Noida and Chennai. Xansas next phase of construction for its offshore development centre in Pune is fast progressing, he said.																								Cox also said the $800-million company has been increasing the scope of services offered as well as the number of clients served. 																								Currently, though most of Xansas clients are UK-based, Cox said it was also working for US firms and other nations. Some of its prominent clients include British Telecom, Barclays, London Electricity, Glaxo Smithkline, AXA Sun Life and Texas Instruments. 
